@John

Pardon my question, but is your point that only gold, silver, and copper are typically found in the metallic state in the earth?  And that the "metal" in ores, such as bauxite and vanadinite, etc, are only partly made of metals?   That the ores contains metal ions, but not a pure metallic solid?

Sorry, I think I remember this coming up in the past, and I don't remember the details.

@John
I really don't get this quibble.

An ore, per M-W, is "a naturally occurring mineral containing a valuable constituent (such as metal)." If I find iron ore in a mine, I have found metal, have I not? How does the clue not fit?

@Katie

As a crossword clue it's fine. But if you find iron ore in a mine, it is almost certainly magnetite or hematite, Fe3O4 or Fe2O3, respectively. These are metallic oxides, but technically not "metals". Of course, both contain the element iron, and pure iron is indeed a metal.

Some metallic elements, copper, silver and gold for example, can be found in native form, uncombined with other elements.

@Xword Junkie

Looks like we agree on the suitability of the clue.

The rest, I get it.  I took earth science in ninth grade, and I know that bauxite is the ORE; aluminum is the metal extracted from it.  Hematite and iron.  And if you're hungry for more, we can throw in apatite.  But I fail to see why that has any relevance to the suitability of the clue and answer.

@Xword Junkie

"has", not "have". 

Good grief.

@Marlene
....well, because there IS such a thing as "good grief"....the kind that leads one through the work of mourning and leads, to consolation.

I am still sad about the mishandling, the demand to conform, the requirement that we all bury our feelings, that left each of us youngsters alone in our sorrow after our grand-dad's untimely death...long, long ago.

